HTTP (80) â†’ 0.0.0.0/0
SSH (22) â†’ Your IP

2ï¸âƒ£ Configure Web Server Using User Data
Use the same user data script for all 3 instances:

#!/bin/bash
apt update -y
apt install nginx -y
systemctl start nginx
systemctl enable nginx
echo "this is test server $HOSTNAME" > /var/www/html/index.html


This ensures:
Nginx installs automatically
Each instance shows its unique hostname

3ï¸âƒ£ Verify EC2 Instances
Confirm all 3 EC2 instances are running
Access each instance via its public IP
You should see different hostnames on each instance

4ï¸âƒ£ Create Classic Load Balancer

Load Balancer type: Classic Load Balancer
Listener: HTTP (80)
Availability Zones: Select AZs where EC2s are running
Register all 3 EC2 instances
Enable health checks

5ï¸âƒ£ Test Load Balancing
Open the CLB DNS name in browser
Refresh the page multiple times
Observe responses rotating between 3 different hostnames
âœ” Confirms load balancing is working.

#Health Check Validation
Navigate to Load Balancer â†’ Instances
All 3 instances should show InService
Stop one EC2 â†’ traffic rotates between remaining instances
Restart â†’ instance returns to service

#Cleanup

Delete Classic Load Balancer
Terminate all 3 EC2 instances
Verify no unused Elastic IPs

